>>46564742
Do you grandpa's even realize how OLD that comic is? Seriously, Dresden Codak is older than some people in this thread right now. Probably.

Anyway, I think it's an interesting example of early webcomics, and how things have changed. Looking back on it, even though I used to love early DC, I don't think it was ever good. Even the earliest comics rely on that type of SCIENCE! referencing that was all the rage in the early 2000's. There was a time when I considered DC to have some of the best webcomic art, but looking at it now I'm not so impressed. It's still good, and it's clear Aaron Diaz took a huge flight in skill when he first started doing this (and then plateau'd hard), but it doesn't have that shine it used to. Diaz just might have been one of this first people with an actual intent to develop his skill to get into webcomics.

But then came the nose dive. Turns out Diaz was an insufferable cunt, and his popularity lead him to believe he had the chops to turn what worked as loose references to a shared mythos and a somewhat cute recurring character into an actual story. He couldn't. It's a bore to read, and it never goes anywhere on account of Diaz only putting out a few pages per year and not knowing a thing about pacing and economic writing. But the nail in the coffin is the author himself. While Diaz was fine as an anonymous SCIENCE! cartoonist, he was poison as a soapboxing pundit with a Big Opinions comic.

I haven't read it in years, obviously. But the one that was the most tragic was a return to his old form. A one-off SCIENCE! gag. It was good. Kinda funny. Something the comic hadn't been in years.

>>46571424
Especially early webcomics were come all, serve all. That's part of what made the entire thing so great in the first place. I'm guessing reasons are different for every author. As you say, these were all just nerds who, by virtue of being nerds, were the first to jump onto a new platform that ended up exploding in unexpected ways. Having a big webcomic in the 2000's was a much bigger deal than having one today, and ultimately the ranting of people like Ishida isn't any different than that of your average Twitter user. It's just more jarring that it moves into that from a relatively benign form, instead of doing the Minimum Security thing and being laughable propaganda from the start.

But it's still there today. It's just that webcomics dropped in popularity while also growing immensely in levels of skill involved. The random nobody gaining a big audience with minimal art skills just doesn't exist anymore. Or at least, not in the numbers they used to.

But if you'd told me back in the day that it's the guy who does TwoKinds who will become the success story of his era, I would have called you nuts.
